1241":"March 1241","1180":"1180","Bude la Vieille":"La Vieille, Hérault, Languedoc-Roussillon, France","Bosnia-Herzegovina":"Bosnia-Herzegovina","Cumania or Mongolia":"Mongolia","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Array","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Armando, Jose, Manuel, Angelina, Araceli, Benigno, Cruz, Estela, Homero, Jesus, Juan, Lucila.  German Erwin, Heino, Kurt, Manfred.","Spanish, French, German, and English: metonymic occupational name for a dealer in a type of heavy woolen cloth for which the city of Arras in northern France (Pas-de-Calais) was internationally famous in the Middle Ages. The cloth was typically used to make tapestry wall hangings. In France, this is also found as a habitational name from Arras.","Scottish: probably a habitatonal name from Airhouse in Channelkirk (Berwickshire), which is recorded as <i>Arous</i> in 1510, <i>Arreis</i> in 1630, and <i>Aras</i> in 1655."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Khan","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Arabic/Muslim Mohammad, Mohammed, Abdul, Muhammad, Mohamed, Bibi, Tariq, Ali, Asif, Khalid, Amir, Saeed.","Muslim (also common among African Americans): from <i>khan</i>, an English spelling of a status name based on Mongolian <i>khaan</i> ‘(military) ruler, sovereign’. This was originally a hereditary title among Tartar and Mongolian tribesmen (in particular Genghis Khan, 1162–1227), but is now very widely used throughout the Muslim world as a surname. In Iran and parts of the Indian subcontinent it is used as an honorific title after a person's name."],"variants":[{"name":"Khanom","meanings":["Muslim (Bangladesh and Iran): from Persian <i>khānum</i> ‘princess, noblewoman’. This is not actually a surname, but a female honorific, the feminine equivalent of   Khan  . Compare   Khanam  ."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Korean Kyong, Kyong Suk, Young, Chae, Chi Young, Hang, Kil, Rin, Sang Hun, Chang, Chong, Insoo, Kum, Sun Young, Yom, Young Hwan.  Cambodian Kiwan, Oeurn, Phoeun, Pich, Saroeuth, Seung, Sophath, Sophea, Yoeun, Phan, Son.  Indian Shanti, Harendra.","Indian (Uttar Pradesh): Brahmin name, from Sanskrit <i>om</i>, the Hindu sacred and mystic syllable uttered at the beginning of prayers.","Cambodian: written ឱម, corresponding to the exclamation of solemn affirmation, of Sanskrit origin (see 1 above), chanted by Buddhist monks."],"variants":[{"name":"Oum","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Southeast Asian Heang, Hye, Kam, Kan, Kheng, Khin, Kun, Sang, Sok, Phong, Yom, Yoo, Youn, Cuong, Phal, Samnang, Tin.  Cambodian Sokha, Chheang, Choeun, Moeun, Roeun, Sambath, Samoeun, Savuth, Soeun, Sopheap.","Cambodian: written អ៊ុំ, from a Khmer word denoting an elder sibling of one's parent (i.e. ‘uncle’ or ‘aunt’). Compare   Om   3 and   Um   2."]}]},{"name":"the","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Vietnamese: unexplained.","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surname 鄭, possibly based on its Hokkien or Teochew pronunciation, see   Zheng   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Zheng","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Jian, Yi, Bin, Hong, Hua, Li, Wei, Yong, Ting, Xin, Yan, Hui, Min, Hao, Shen, Da, Quan, Tian, Chong.","Chinese:","Mandarin form of the surname 鄭: from Zheng (鄭), the name of a state (located in part of present-day Shaanxi and Henan provinces) granted to You, the younger brother of King Xuan of Zhou (reigned 827–782  BC ). The state of Zheng was annexed by the state of Han (located in present-day Shaanxi and Henan provinces) during the Warring States period (475–221  BC )."]}]},{"name":"Khan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names 